---
import DocsLayout from '../../layouts/DocsLayout.astro';
import Icon from '../../components/Icon.astro';
import Terminal from '../../components/Terminal.astro';
---

<DocsLayout
  title="Agent Lifecycle"
  description="Five states, context-pressure thresholds, turn-boundary drain snapshots, graceful-then-forced kill protocol, and the ephemeral-by-design principle that makes crash recovery tractable."
  sectionLabel="REFERENCE // AGENT_LIFECYCLE"
>
  <p class="font-headline text-lg text-on-surface-variant italic leading-relaxed max-w-xl mb-12">
    Agents are ephemeral by design. State lives in the filesystem and the audit log. The kernel owns a small state machine that moves each agent from healthy execution through context pressure into a graceful finalization turn, then death.
  </p>

  <!-- State machine -->
  <section class="mb-16">
    <h2 class="section-label mb-6">STATE_MACHINE</h2>
    <p class="font-body text-xs text-secondary mb-6 max-w-lg">
      Five states, no regression. Once an agent advances, it cannot go back. Source: <code class="text-primary">src/kernel/lifecycle.rs:56–76, 132–135</code>.
    </p>
    <div class="space-y-px">
      {[
        {
          state: 'HEALTHY',
          trigger: 'Default state at spawn. Context &lt; 70%.',
          behavior: 'Normal execution. All tool calls permitted, no instrumentation overhead.',
        },
        {
          state: 'AGING',
          trigger: 'Context ≥ 70% (AGING_THRESHOLD_PCT). lifecycle.rs:22',
          behavior: 'Still executing. The kernel begins preparing a handoff record for a successor agent. No compaction — the agent\'s context is not mutated mid-turn.',
        },
        {
          state: 'DYING',
          trigger: 'Context ≥ 90% (DYING_THRESHOLD_PCT). Context jumps (e.g. 60% → 92%) skip AGING and go straight to DYING. lifecycle.rs:23, 138–140',
          behavior: 'Critical. No new tool calls allowed beyond the finalization turn. Handoff data is finalized.',
        },
        {
          state: 'DRAINING',
          trigger: 'One finalization turn allowed after DYING.',
          behavior: 'Single last tool call permitted — typically the handoff write. After this turn completes, the state advances to DEAD.',
        },
        {
          state: 'DEAD',
          trigger: 'Finalization turn complete, or context pressure past recovery.',
          behavior: 'All tool calls fenced. The agent process is a zombie until the daemon reaps it.',
        },
      ].map(s => (
        <div class="bg-surface-container grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-12">
          <div class="md:col-span-2 bg-surface-container-low px-4 py-5 flex items-center">
            <span class="font-body text-sm font-bold text-primary">{s.state}</span>
          </div>
          <div class="md:col-span-5 px-4 py-5">
            <div class="font-label text-[10px] text-outline mb-1">TRIGGER</div>
            <span class="font-body text-xs text-secondary" set:html={s.trigger}></span>
          </div>
          <div class="md:col-span-5 px-4 py-5">
            <div class="font-label text-[10px] text-outline mb-1">BEHAVIOR</div>
            <span class="font-body text-xs text-secondary">{s.behavior}</span>
          </div>
        </div>
      ))}
    </div>
    <p class="font-body text-xs text-secondary mt-4 max-w-lg">
      Transitions are guarded by <code class="text-primary">LifecycleState::can_transition_to()</code> at <code class="text-primary">lifecycle.rs:66–76</code>. The transition driver is <code class="text-primary">lifecycle.evaluate(context_pct)</code>, called from dispatch at <code class="text-primary">src/serve/dispatch.rs:909–913</code>.
    </p>
  </section>

  <!-- Context pressure -->
  <section class="mb-16">
    <h2 class="serif-text text-3xl font-medium text-on-surface mb-4">How Context Pressure is Detected</h2>
    <div class="bg-surface-container-low p-6 border-l-2 border-primary">
      <p class="font-body text-xs text-secondary mb-3">
        The kernel does <span class="text-primary font-bold">not</span> auto-compress context mid-turn. Context pressure is a signal, not an intervention point. The mechanism:
      </p>
      <ol class="font-body text-xs text-secondary list-decimal pl-5 space-y-2">
        <li>Each turn, <code class="text-primary">PreCallTokenCount</code> and <code class="text-primary">Usage</code> events update the session's token state.</li>
        <li>Dispatch computes <code class="text-primary">context_pct</code> from those counts and calls <code class="text-primary">lifecycle.evaluate(context_pct)</code>.</li>
        <li>If the threshold crosses, the state advances monotonically (Healthy → Aging → Dying → Draining → Dead). A sudden jump can skip states — a 60% → 92% crossing goes straight from Healthy to Dying without stopping at Aging.</li>
        <li>The current turn still completes. Fencing only kicks in when the next turn is requested.</li>
      </ol>
      <p class="font-body text-xs text-secondary mt-4">
        Context pressure triggers a <span class="text-primary">handoff</span> — a structured record the next agent inherits — not in-flight compaction. The design choice is explicit: mutating context mid-turn would defeat the prompt cache and surprise the model.
      </p>
      <p class="font-body text-[10px] text-outline mt-4">
        Source: <code class="text-primary">src/kernel/lifecycle.rs:22–23</code> (thresholds), <code class="text-primary">src/serve/dispatch.rs:909</code> (call site), <code class="text-primary">src/kernel/lifecycle.rs:138–140</code> (skip behavior, test coverage at line 460).
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Spawn -->
  <section class="mb-16">
    <h2 class="section-label mb-4">SPAWN</h2>
    <div class="space-y-px">
      {[
        { step: '01', action: 'Operator runs ostk kernel spawn <name> --model sonnet --budget 5 "task description". Or internally via ostk _agent.' },
        { step: '02', action: 'Daemon fork-exec\'s a subprocess (not an in-process thread). The agent is a real OS process with its own PID.' },
        { step: '03', action: 'Agent writes .ostk/agents/<name>.meta with real PID and config. agent_cmd.rs:33–46.' },
        { step: '04', action: 'Agent binds a UnixListener at .ostk/agents/<name>.sock. This is how detachable clients attach. agent_cmd.rs:88–96.' },
        { step: '05', action: 'Lineage ID is the alias passed via --name. Lineage = the stable identity the daemon tracks across restarts; it outlives any single process.' },
      ].map(s => (
        <div class="bg-surface-container grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-12">
          <div class="md:col-span-1 bg-surface-container-low flex items-center justify-center py-3">
            <span class="serif-text text-lg font-bold text-primary">{s.step}</span>
          </div>
          <div class="md:col-span-11 px-4 py-3">
            <span class="font-body text-xs text-secondary">{s.action}</span>
          </div>
        </div>
      ))}
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Heartbeat -->
  <section class="mb-16">
    <h2 class="section-label mb-4">HEARTBEAT_AND_CRASH_DETECTION</h2>
    <div class="bg-surface-container-low p-6 border-l-2 border-primary">
      <p class="font-body text-xs text-secondary mb-3">
        Timestamp-based, not socket-based. Each agent writes its <code class="text-primary">last_seen</code> ISO8601 to <code class="text-primary">.ostk/agents.jsonl</code> on every turn. The daemon interprets staleness:
      </p>
      <div class="grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-3 gap-px bg-surface-variant">
        <div class="bg-surface-container p-4">
          <div class="font-label text-[10px] text-primary mb-1">ACTIVE</div>
          <p class="font-body text-xs text-secondary">last_seen &lt; 30s ago. Agent is actively ticking.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="bg-surface-container p-4">
          <div class="font-label text-[10px] text-primary mb-1">STALE</div>
          <p class="font-body text-xs text-secondary">30s–90s. Idle but probably alive. Daemon does not intervene yet.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="bg-surface-container p-4">
          <div class="font-label text-[10px] text-primary mb-1">CRASHED</div>
          <p class="font-body text-xs text-secondary">&gt; 90s. Daemon calls <code class="text-primary">kill(pid, 0)</code> to distinguish idle-alive from actually-dead.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <p class="font-body text-[10px] text-outline mt-4">
        Source: <code class="text-primary">src/kernel/heartbeat.rs:47–54, 89–91</code> (thresholds and is_alive probe). Turn-based fallback state per agent at <code class="text-primary">.ostk/.heartbeat.&lt;alias&gt;</code> is tracked at <code class="text-primary">heartbeat.rs:228–240</code>.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Drain snapshot -->
  <section class="mb-16">
    <h2 class="serif-text text-3xl font-medium text-on-surface mb-4">Drain Snapshots</h2>
    <p class="font-body text-xs text-secondary mb-6 max-w-lg">
      At every turn boundary (after each assistant response completes), the session hook writes a snapshot to <code class="text-primary">.ostk/drain/&lt;lineage_id&gt;.json</code>. Wave G.3 flipped this to default ON — previously opt-in via <code class="text-primary">OSTK_DRAIN_SNAPSHOT=1</code>. Source: <code class="text-primary">src/kernel/drain.rs:102–111</code>, hook at <code class="text-primary">src/cpu/session.rs:1030</code>.
    </p>
    <h3 class="section-label-secondary mb-3">SNAPSHOT_V2_CONTENTS</h3>
    <div class="bg-surface-container-lowest p-6 border border-surface-variant mb-4">
      <pre class="font-body text-xs text-secondary leading-relaxed"><span class="text-primary">lineage_id</span>      <span class="text-outline"># stable identity</span>
<span class="text-primary">anchor_id</span>       <span class="text-outline"># daemon instance that wrote this</span>
<span class="text-primary">written_at</span>      <span class="text-outline"># ISO8601 timestamp</span>
<span class="text-primary">model</span>           <span class="text-outline"># LLM model string</span>
<span class="text-primary">session_tokens</span>  <span class="text-outline"># input/output/cache_read/cache_create cumulative</span>
<span class="text-primary">messages</span>        <span class="text-outline"># full conversation history</span>
<span class="text-primary">config</span>          <span class="text-outline"># pruned LoopConfig: tools, max_tokens, permission_mode,</span>
                <span class="text-outline">#   thinking, citations, tool_patterns, revival_policy</span></pre>
    </div>
    <p class="font-body text-xs text-secondary mb-3 max-w-lg">
      What's <span class="text-primary">not</span> in a snapshot (deliberately ephemeral):
    </p>
    <ul class="font-body text-xs text-secondary list-disc pl-5 space-y-1 mb-4">
      <li><code class="text-primary">root</code>, <code class="text-primary">preload_context</code> — daemon-local pointers regenerated at boot</li>
      <li><code class="text-primary">pending_images</code>, <code class="text-primary">outbox</code> — transient turn state</li>
      <li><code class="text-primary">runtime_allowed</code> — session approval list, rebuilt per run</li>
      <li><code class="text-primary">task_handle</code>, <code class="text-primary">cancel_flag</code>, event channels — tokio primitives, not serializable</li>
    </ul>
    <p class="font-body text-[10px] text-outline">
      Source: <code class="text-primary">src/kernel/drain.rs:81–88, 192–221</code>.
    </p>
  </section>

  <!-- Kill and reap -->
  <section class="mb-16">
    <h2 class="section-label mb-4">KILL_AND_REAP</h2>
    <p class="font-body text-xs text-secondary mb-6 max-w-lg">
      Two different operations. Kill terminates a running process; reap compacts the registry after the process is already dead.
    </p>
    <div class="grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-2 gap-px bg-surface-variant">
      <div class="bg-surface-container p-6">
        <div class="font-label text-[10px] text-primary mb-2">KILL (session_proctable)</div>
        <ol class="font-body text-xs text-secondary list-decimal pl-4 space-y-2">
          <li>SIGTERM to the process group (negative PID). session_proctable.rs:161.</li>
          <li>Five-second grace period. session_proctable.rs:170–171.</li>
          <li>SIGKILL fallback if the process is still alive. session_proctable.rs:179.</li>
        </ol>
        <p class="font-body text-[10px] text-outline mt-4">No final drain write — session_proctable handles in-process background tasks.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="bg-surface-container p-6">
        <div class="font-label text-[10px] text-primary mb-2">REAP (ostk kernel reap)</div>
        <ol class="font-body text-xs text-secondary list-decimal pl-4 space-y-2">
          <li>Read <code class="text-primary">.ostk/agents.jsonl</code>, probe each "active" entry with <code class="text-primary">kill(pid, 0)</code>. reap.rs:69–128.</li>
          <li>For entries whose process is already dead: flip status, remove from active set.</li>
          <li>Rewrite a compacted <code class="text-primary">agents.jsonl</code>.</li>
          <li>Call <code class="text-primary">cleanup_agent_state()</code> (heartbeat.rs:304) to remove per-agent files.</li>
        </ol>
        <p class="font-body text-[10px] text-outline mt-4">Reap is a post-mortem sweep. It does not send signals — if a process is still running it's left alone.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Rehydration -->
  <section class="mb-16">
    <h2 class="serif-text text-3xl font-medium text-on-surface mb-4">Crash Recovery</h2>
    <div class="bg-surface-container-low p-6 border-l-2 border-primary">
      <p class="font-body text-xs text-secondary mb-3">
        When the daemon restarts, <code class="text-primary">SessionManager::with_anchor</code> reads drain snapshots for orphaned lineages and rehydrates them. Source: <code class="text-primary">src/kernel/drain.rs:21–27</code>.
      </p>
      <ul class="font-body text-xs text-secondary list-disc pl-5 space-y-2">
        <li>Messages and token state are restored from the snapshot.</li>
        <li>Config is either refreshed from the live Agentfile template or carried over from the snapshot.</li>
        <li><code class="text-primary">SnapshotV2::upgrade_from_v1()</code> handles pre-G.1 snapshots (config=None on upgrade). drain.rs:253–264.</li>
        <li>After successful rehydrate, the snapshot is cleared. drain.rs:29–33.</li>
      </ul>
      <p class="font-body text-xs text-secondary mt-4">
        <span class="text-primary font-bold">Honest caveat:</span> recovery is snapshot-to-restart-point only. Tool calls that happened <em>after</em> the last snapshot write are lost. Rehydration is not full audit replay — the audit log is for observability, the snapshot is for resumption. The two are complementary, not redundant.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Ephemeral by design -->
  <section class="mb-16">
    <h2 class="serif-text text-3xl font-medium text-on-surface mb-4">Ephemeral by Design</h2>
    <p class="font-body text-xs text-secondary mb-6 max-w-lg">
      "Agents are ephemeral" is Five Laws #2 and it is load-bearing. Specific consequences:
    </p>
    <div class="space-y-3">
      {[
        { claim: 'Session state MUST NOT persist across restarts', why: 'Preload context (registers, .language identity blocks) is regenerated at boot. Pinning to a pre-crash cache prefix defeats cache efficiency. drain.rs:221–224.' },
        { claim: 'Token accounting resets on rehydrate', why: 'session_tokens are zeroed, not accumulated from disk. The new process starts its own budget. session.rs:4840.' },
        { claim: 'Task handles are tokio-bound', why: 'task_handle and event channels cannot be deserialized. Rehydrated sessions get fresh tokio primitives. drain.rs:85–88.' },
        { claim: 'In-flight outbox is transient', why: 'Tool results that were mid-flight when the process died are discarded. Rehydration resumes from the snapshot\'s message boundary, not mid-tool. drain.rs:82–84.' },
      ].map(e => (
        <div class="bg-surface-container grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-12">
          <div class="md:col-span-5 bg-surface-container-low px-4 py-4">
            <span class="font-body text-xs text-primary font-bold">{e.claim}</span>
          </div>
          <div class="md:col-span-7 px-4 py-4">
            <span class="font-body text-xs text-secondary">{e.why}</span>
          </div>
        </div>
      ))}
    </div>
    <p class="font-body text-xs text-secondary mt-6 max-w-lg">
      The principle's origin statement, from <code class="text-primary">src/kernel/presence.rs:30–35</code>:
    </p>
    <div class="bg-surface-container-lowest p-4 border border-surface-variant mt-2">
      <p class="font-body text-xs text-secondary italic">
        "State is held in ServerState and resets on daemon restart. Arrivals are not themselves persistent kernel state — the persistent record is the audit row stream, which recall @arrived can query as the canonical arrival record."
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <div class="metadata-ribbon border-t border-surface-variant">
    <span class="font-label text-[10px] text-secondary mr-4">RELATED:</span>
    <a href="/docs/session-topology"><Icon name="hub" size="14" class="align-middle mr-1" />SESSION_TOPOLOGY</a>
    <a href="/docs/five-laws"><Icon name="gavel" size="14" class="align-middle mr-1" />FIVE_LAWS</a>
    <a href="/docs/kernel-spec"><Icon name="memory" size="14" class="align-middle mr-1" />KERNEL_SPEC</a>
    <a href="/docs/agentfile"><Icon name="smart_toy" size="14" class="align-middle mr-1" />AGENTFILE</a>
  </div>
</DocsLayout>
